"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997241","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-05","<p>Under the 13th Programme of Law Reform, the Law Commission expected to complete its project on the law of wills in 2019. It is currently reviewing that timetable in the light of its wider programme of work.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-11-05T17:01:13.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997241/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997241/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-29","Wills","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice,  what the timetable is for the Law Commission to submit its report on wills.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","184914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997242","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-11-05","<p>I can confirm that members of the Ugandan armed forces have received intelligence training provided by the UK, but it is not our practice to comment in detail on the nature of intelligence relationships with other nations. HM Government provides no support to Uganda's Police Rapid Response Unit. As part of our engagement we emphasise the importance of professional forces operating within the framework of international law.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-11-05T16:57:32.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997242/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997242/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997242/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-29","Uganda: Military Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the Answer of 16 October 2018 to Question 176667 on Uganda: Military Aid, what training and support the Government offers to (a) Uganda's Chieftaincy of Military Intelligence and (b) Uganda's Police Rapid Response Unit.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Williams","Stockton South","Dr Paul Williams","185121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997243","Home Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>The information requested is not published. The available information relates to refugee family reunion visa granted, published in the quarterly Immigration Statistics at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/immigration-statistics-quarterly-release</a> .</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-11-06T17:29:13.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997243/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997243/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-29","Refugees: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2018 to Question 173568 on Refugees: Families and with reference to table as_21_q of the Home Office Asylum tables volume 5, how many of the refugee family reunion visas that were granted in 2017 were subsequently used.","false","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan","185007"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997244","Home Office","false","2018-11-06","<p>The information requested is not available. The Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration’s report did not publish full data on the number of cases referred for consideration of leave outside the rules which were subsequently granted and this information does not form part of published immigration statistics.</p><p>Published Home Office statistics relating to family reunion applications can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-june-2018/list-of-tables#asylum%20" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-year-ending-june-2018/list-of-tables#asylum </a></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-11-06T17:27:08.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997244/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997244/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-10-29","Refugees: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 14 September 2018 to Question 173569 on Refugees: Families and with reference to the Figure 4 of the Independent Chief Inspector of Borders and Immigration’s report entitled A re-inspection of the family reunion process, focusing on applications received at the Amman Entry Clearance Decision Making Centre November 2017 – April 2018 published in September 2018, how many of the 81 family reunion applications referred for consideration for leave outside the rules in 2017 were subsequently granted.","false","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan","185008"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997245","Treasury","false","2018-11-01","<p>HM Treasury carefully considers the impacts of policy choices on households at different levels of income. The department publishes distributional analysis of the impacts of decisions on tax, welfare, and spending on public services at each fiscal event, and has done so since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>The government has set out that it is committed to tackling the root causes of poverty, including education and worklessness. This approach is working, with 1,000,000 fewer people, including 300,000 fewer children, in absolute poverty (before housing costs) since 2010, both record lows.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-11-01T13:36:29.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997245/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997245/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-29","Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 25 October 2018 to Question 182119 on Poverty, what steps he is taking to empower civil servants in his Department deliver on civil service competency 8 delivering value for money in the context of policy formulation relating to poverty reduction.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","184915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997246","Treasury","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Government’s proposals, as set out in the 12 July White Paper, are the best way to protect jobs and avoid a hard border between Ireland and Northern Ireland. With negotiations ongoing, it would not be practical or sensible to set out the details of exactly how the Government will assess the final deal. When we bring forward the vote on the final deal, Parliament will be presented with the appropriate analysis to make an informed decision.</p><p> </p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-11-01T13:21:45.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997246/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997246/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997246/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-29","Personal Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Chequers proposals set out in the Government's White Paper entitled The future relationship between the United Kingdom and the European Union, published in July 2018, whether the Government has made an assessment of the potential effect of the Chequers proposals on average net household income.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","184840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997247","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-06","<p>Yes. Technical discussions to support the Crown Dependencies’ own contingency planning are taking place on a regular basis. Jersey’s Minister for External Relations, and the Chief Ministers of Guernsey and the Isle of Man, last month met with the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State with responsibility for Contingency Planning at the Department for Exiting the European Union to discuss this work.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2018-11-06T17:18:08.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997247/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997247/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997247/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-29","Jersey","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, whether the UK Government is including Jersey into its no-deal contingency planning.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","184841"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997248","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) should have regard to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) guideline on the assessment and treatment of people with fertility problems when commissioning services for which they are responsible. This includes the recommendation in the guideline that three cycles of in-vitro fertilisation be offered to qualifying couples where the woman is under the age of 40 and one cycle where the woman is between the ages of 40 and 42.</p><p> </p><p>The NICE guideline is evidence based best practice for clinicians but is not mandatory. The availability of National Health Service funded fertility treatment is matter for local determination. Decisions on the level of service provision are underpinned by clinical insight and knowledge of local healthcare needs and priorities.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the commissioning of fertility services is not collected centrally but an annual survey is undertaken by Fertility Fairness. This can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.fertilityfairness.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/England-FertilityFairness_FOI_2018.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.fertilityfairness.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/England-FertilityFairness_FOI_2018.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-11-01T16:52:39.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997248/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997248/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that Clinical Commissioning Groups meet guidelines that IVF should be offered to women until age 42; what estimate he has made of the number of Clinical Commissioning Groups that do not meet these guidelines; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Layla Moran","Oxford West and Abingdon","Layla Moran","185122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997249","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-11-06T16:24:56.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997249/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997249/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","Hearing Aids: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent estimate he has made of the length of NHS waiting times for children waiting for hearing aid repairs.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","185009"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997250","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-01","<p>Earlier this year, my department provided local authorities and the police with guidance which reminded them of the measures and powers they have in order both to prevent and to deal with dangerous dog attacks. These measures include the ability to issue Community Protection Notices to individuals whose dogs are causing low level nuisance, and hence to intervene before a dog becomes dangerous. Other measures include using the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 where a dog is considered to be dangerously out of control, in any place. The guidance, as with the measures, apply regardless as to whether the dog has attacked pets, livestock or wild animals. My officials have also confirmed with the National Police Chief Constables Livestock Offences Group that the Dangerous Dogs Act 1991 can be used in cases of attacks on other dogs or other animals, regardless as to whether a person was present.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-11-01T10:38:14.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997250/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997250/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-29","Dangerous Dogs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what guidance his Department has given to local authorities to prevent dog attacks on (a) domestic pets, (b) livestock and (c) wild animals.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","185010"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997251","Treasury","false","2018-11-01","<p>The apprenticeship programme is based on employer demand. Therefore, HMT do not hold information on how funding is distributed regionally.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-11-01T16:10:18.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997251/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997251/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997251/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-29","Apprentices: South Yorkshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to his Department’s announcement, Package of measures unveiled to boost apprenticeships, published in October 2018, how much and what proportion of the £90 million of additional funding will be allocated to (a) South Yorkshire and (b) Barnsley.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","185011"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997252","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-01","<p>The funding will be available across England; there are no plans for funding on a regional basis.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-11-01T10:30:51.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997252/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997252/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997252/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-29","Food: Waste","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, with reference to his Department's announcement, Action to reduce food waste announced, published in October 2018, how much of the £15 million additional funding will be allocated to South Yorkshire.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","185012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997253","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>The data is not available in the format requested.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-01T16:53:25.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997253/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997253/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997253/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","Asthma: Barnsley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many (a) adults and (b) children attended  Barnsley Hospital A&E as a result of asthma in each of the last five years; and what steps his Department is taking to reduce the number of A&E admissions for asthma.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","185013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997254","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>The information requested is shown in the following tables.</p><p> </p><p>A count of finished admission episodes for children and adults in the government office region of Yorkshire and the Humber with a primary diagnosis of asthma.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Age 0-17 years</p></td><td><p>Age 18-120 years</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>2,447</p></td><td><p>4,147</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>2,616</p></td><td><p>4,933</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>2,135</p></td><td><p>4,926</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>2,212</p></td><td><p>5,191</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>2,173</p></td><td><p>4,971</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>A count of finished admission episodes for children and adults in England with a primary diagnosis of asthma.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Age 0-17 years</p></td><td><p>Age 18-120 years</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/14</p></td><td><p>25,841</p></td><td><p>39,916</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>28,710</p></td><td><p>46,900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>27,355</p></td><td><p>46,845</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17</p></td><td><p>27,609</p></td><td><p>49,583</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017/18</p></td><td><p>26,088</p></td><td><p>52,219</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Source: Hospital Episode Statistics (HES), NHS Digital</p><p> </p><p>Notes:</p><ol><li>A finished admission episode (FAE) is the first period of inpatient care under one consultant within one healthcare provider. FAEs are counted against the year in which the admission episode finishes. Admissions do not represent the number of inpatients, as a person may have more than one admission within the year.</li><li>The government office region of residence of the patient is derived from the patient's postcode in the field home address.</li><li>The primary diagnosis is the first of up to 20 (14 from 2002-03 to 2006-07 and seven prior to 2002-03) diagnosis fields in the HES data set and provides the main reason why the patient was admitted to hospital.</li><li>Asthma clinical codes used: J45 and J46</li><li>HES figures are available from 1989-90 onwards. Changes to the figures over time need to be interpreted in the context of improvements in data quality and coverage (particularly in earlier years), improvements in coverage of independent sector activity (particularly from 2006-07) and changes in National Health Service practice. For example, apparent reductions in activity may be due to a number of procedures which may now be undertaken in outpatient settings and so no longer include admitted patient HES data. Conversely, apparent increases in activity may be due to improved recording of diagnosis or procedure information.</li><li>It should be noted that HES include activity ending in the year in question and run from April to March, e.g. 2015-16 includes activity ending between 1 April 2015 and 31 March 2016.</li></ol>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-01T16:52:42.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997254/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997254/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997254/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","Asthma","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many (a) adults and (b) children were admitted to hospital as a result of asthma in (a) Yorkshire and the Humber and (b) England in each of the last five years.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","185014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997255","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-01","<p>Private Pensions information will be available through dashboards. Delivery of these will be led by industry and facilitated by government. We will set out and consult on our proposed approach to delivery, including how to maximise private pension schemes participation in the dashboard in our feasibility report, which will be published shortly.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>People can already access the online ‘Check your State Pension’ service through GOV.UK to get a forecast of their State Pension. This includes information about how they may be able to improve the amount of State Pension they are entitled to, as well as providing a view of their National Insurance contribution record. Check Your State Pension service has provided more than ten million online estimates since its introduction in 2016.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","185016","2018-11-01T15:42:44.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997255/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997255/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997255/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-29","Pensions: Consumer Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps she is taking to ensure that private pensions are accessible through the pensions dashboard.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","185015"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997256","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-01","<p>Private Pensions information will be available through dashboards. Delivery of these will be led by industry and facilitated by government. We will set out and consult on our proposed approach to delivery, including how to maximise private pension schemes participation in the dashboard in our feasibility report, which will be published shortly.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>People can already access the online ‘Check your State Pension’ service through GOV.UK to get a forecast of their State Pension. This includes information about how they may be able to improve the amount of State Pension they are entitled to, as well as providing a view of their National Insurance contribution record. Check Your State Pension service has provided more than ten million online estimates since its introduction in 2016.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman","185015","2018-11-01T15:42:44.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997256/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997256/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997256/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-29","Pensions: Consumer Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will take steps to ensure that State Pension information is accessible through the pensions dashboard to enable (a) pensioners and (b) people approaching retirement age to make informed decisions.","false","Biography information for Owen Smith","Pontypridd","Owen Smith","185016"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997257","Treasury","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Government wants to ensure tenants in receipt of housing benefit are able to access suitable properties.</p><p> </p><p>UK Finance has assured us that the majority of active Buy-to-Let lenders do not prevent landlords leasing properties to tenants in receipt of social security benefits. Therefore, any landlord who wants to let to benefit claimants should be able to easily find a lender who will allow that.</p><p> </p><p>It is also worth noting that only about a third of private rental properties are financed by a buy to let mortgage.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-11-06T16:02:28.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997257/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997257/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997257/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-10-29","Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure that mortgage lenders do not prevent landlords leasing properties to tenants in receipt of social security benefits.","false","Biography information for John Healey","Wentworth and Dearne","John Healey","184871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997258","Department for Education","false","2018-11-01","<p>The reception baseline assessment was trialled in a nationally representative sample of schools between 10 September and 19 October 2018. Schools’ participation in the trials was voluntary.</p><p> </p><p>In line with accepted practice, the names of the schools that are participating in these trials will not be released by the department. Schools were recruited on this basis and releasing this information could adversely affect school participation in future voluntary trialling, which would put our ability to develop high quality, valid and reliable assessments at risk.</p><p> </p><p>In our response to the public consultation on the future of the primary assessment system in England, and having noted the support from respondents to that consultation exercise, we confirmed that we would introduce a reception baseline assessment from the 2020 to 2021 academic year onwards. As part of that, we committed to explore the issue of what information from the assessment should be shared with schools. That consideration is continuing and we will make a further announcement prior to the introduction of the assessment.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi","185091","2018-11-01T14:12:11.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997258/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997258/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997258/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-29","Pre-School Education: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether his Department has received representations on the legality of a child's data being collected through baseline assessment testing but not accessible to (a) the child, (b) the parents of the child and (c) education staff; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","185123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997259","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-06","<p>The introduction of the General Data Protection Regulations (GDPR) increased the obligations on both data controllers and processors in respect of data sharing. DWP engages with all of its Agencies (Arm’s Length Bodies (ALBs)). Each ALB is also required to provide a Certificate of Assurance regarding compliance with GDPR regulations. Any representations on the effectiveness of data sharing with the Department will be addressed in line with the GDPR. At the moment there are none to consider.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2018-11-06T16:04:14.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997259/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997259/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997259/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-29","Department for Work and Pensions: Databases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what representations she has received from agencies of her Department on the effectiveness of data sharing with her Department.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","184872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997261","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>The NHS Business Services Authority (BSA) actively prepares, circulates and promotes information for the public on Prescription Prepayment Certificates as part of its duties in administering this service. The funding information requested cannot be provided, as it is not separately identified.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-11-06T15:26:06.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997261/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997261/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997261/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","Prescriptions: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what funding his Department has allocated to the promotion of public information on prescription prepayment certificates.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","184873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997262","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Mine Countermeasures and Hydrographic Capability project has successfully completed the first part of its Assessment Phase. The key output to date has been the successful demonstration of an unmanned minesweeping capability.</p>","Pudsey","Stuart Andrew",,"2018-11-01T15:18:48.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997262/answer","Biography information for Stuart Andrew","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997262/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997262/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-10-29","Minesweepers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what progress his Department has made on the Countermeasures and Hydrographic Capability project.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","184916"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997263","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-01","<p>As the Youth Obligation Support Programme, is being rolled out across the country as part of the broader Universal Credit roll-out, we are using a test and learn process to deliver our services. We are currently reviewing how we best collect and assimilate data on the Youth Obligation Support Programme, to assure ourselves of its delivery.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","184843","2018-11-01T16:35:50.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997263/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997263/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997263/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-29","Employment Schemes: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people (a) have started the Youth Obligation Support Programme and (b) are taking part in the Youth Obligation Support Programme for the most recent period for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","184842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997264","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>Due to a number of systemic changes, including those made as a result of the Health and Social Care Act 2012, trust deficit figures within the National Health Service are not comparable with those in 2010. In seven of the last eight years the Department has lived within its total revenue budget – which covers the entire health and social care system. This is the key metric of financial performance for the NHS i.e. whether in aggregate the NHS over, or under-spent.</p><p> </p><p>Fewer trusts are in deficit and the size of those deficits are down compared to 2015-16. But problems in a minority of trusts do still exist, and tackling that challenge is key to the success of the NHS’s plan.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-11-01T17:43:12.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997264/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997264/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997264/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","NHS Trusts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October to Question 178506 on NHS Trusts: Standards, whether (a) the NHS provider deficit, (b) the size of individual trust deficits, and (c) the number of trusts reporting a deficit, have improved since 2010-11, and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","185017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997265","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-11-01","<p>As the Youth Obligation Support Programme, is being rolled out across the country as part of the broader Universal Credit roll-out, we are using a test and learn process to deliver our services. We are currently reviewing how we best collect and assimilate data on the Youth Obligation Support Programme, to assure ourselves of its delivery.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","184842","2018-11-01T16:35:50.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997265/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997265/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997265/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-10-29","Employment Schemes: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when she plans to update the number of Youth Obligation Support Programme (a) starters and (b) participants.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","184843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997266","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>NHS Improvement publish a tariff uplift as part of its role as regulator; to use as the starting basis for which prices and contracts should be negotiated in the National Health Service. The construct includes a thorough assessment of pressures e.g. pay, drugs etc. and the scale of potential off-setting efficiencies. This process ensures a fair but challenging delivery requirement for the NHS. The calculation enabled sufficient funding for the majority of organisations to end 2017-18 in surplus. As part of the Long Term Plan, the tariff mechanism is being reviewed to ensure it remains fit for purpose.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-11-01T17:44:06.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997266/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997266/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997266/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","NHS Trusts: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to the Answer of 23 October to Question 178506 on NHS Trusts: Standards, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of below inflation increases to the NHS tariff on NHS provider deficits since 2010-11, and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","185018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997267","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>We expect this to be published by NHS Digital on 22 November 2018, as part of the Mental Health of Children and Young People in England, 2017 publication.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-11-01T16:50:37.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997267/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997267/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997267/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","Health: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to publish the National Study of Health and Wellbeing: Children and Young People.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","185019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997268","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Secretary of State for Health and Social Care meets regularly with Cabinet colleagues to discuss a wide range of important issues.</p><p> </p><p>The Department, through the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) invests in a wide range of research on children and families, including a new Children and Families Policy Research Unit which will start in January 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the NIHR’s Global Health Research Team has met twice this year with United Kingdom funders of research for International Development convened by the UK Collaborative on Development Research to discuss existing and future investment in reproductive, maternal and neonatal health research. Participants include the Department for International Development, Welcome Trust and UK Research and Innovation.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-11-01T16:49:48.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997268/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997268/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997268/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","Health: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on the promotion of research into child heath by (a) UK Research and Innovation and (b) UK higher educational institutions.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","185020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997269","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-01","<p>There are no current plans to reinstate the Infant Feeding Survey.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-11-01T16:51:32.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997269/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997269/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997269/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","Infant Foods","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has plans to reinstate the Infant Feeding Survey.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","185021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997270","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-11-08","<p>The attached table shows the amount spent by the Department of Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on paid social media activity in support of Communication Campaigns. This includes the Shared Parental Leave Campaign, to promote take up of SPL among eligible parents, and the National Living and National Minimum Wage Campaign, to increase awareness of the increases in NLW/NMW and of the complaint’s procedure. It also supported awareness of the Green Great Britain Week, setting out how job opportunities would be created by the move to clean growth.</p><p> </p><p>The table is split for each of the following Social Media channels (Twitter, Facebook and Instagram) and is shown per month from June 2017 until the end of October 2018.</p><p> </p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2018-11-08T16:40:19.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997270/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997270/answer","185022 BEIS spend on social media.docx","BEIS  - social media ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997270/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-10-29","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much his Department has spent from the public purse on promoted content on (a) Twitter, (b) Facebook and (c) Instagram in each month since June 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","185022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997271","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-01","<p>No. It is not the Government's role to set retail food prices or to comment on day-to-day commercial decisions by companies. Our research has found that consumer food prices depend on a range of factors, including commodity prices, currency exchange rates, and oil prices, and this will continue to be the case when we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>We work closely with industry to promote transparency for consumers and internationally to promote open global markets. The work we are doing helps to support a competitive domestic market so producers and retailers can offer the best prices.</p><p> </p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-11-01T14:46:33.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997271/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997271/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997271/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-29","Food: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department has plans to introduce legislative proposals to regulate food prices after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","184917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997272","Department for Education","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Department for Education (DfE) uses digital advertising as a cost effective way to reach target audiences, to deliver awareness and behaviour change campaigns to support government priorities such as recruiting teachers, starting apprenticeships and tackling child abuse.</p><p>In line with other government departments we buy media space through the government appointed media buying agency, Carat. The majority of our spend is on the department’s teacher recruitment campaign. In the financial year 2017-18, DfE purchased media space on Facebook, Twitter and Instagram to the value of £1,581,186.99. In 2018-19 to the end of September we spent £640,931.55. Ad hoc spend may not be included in this amount. On occasion, there may be some spend in certain months which will carry over into the following month.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-11-06T14:53:37.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997272/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997272/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997272/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-10-29","Department for Education: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much his Department has spent from the public purse on promoted content on (a) Twitter, (b) Facebook and (c) Instagram in each month since June 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","185023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997273","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-11-01","<p>The Secretary of State has regular discussions with the DExEU Secretary and other Cabinet colleagues about our readiness for leaving the EU. In recent weeks the Government published a range of technical notices which provided information on preparations for leaving the EU, including importing and exporting.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2018-11-01T14:26:04.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997273/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997273/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997273/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-10-29","Food: UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union on the importation of food from EU countries after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for David Simpson","Upper Bann","David Simpson","184918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997274","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-11-06","<p>Digital advertising is a cost-effective way for the government to recruit prison officers, help people find out about the courts process and all the other important information the public needs to be aware of.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice has spent £171,635.80 on promoted activity with these platforms over the period of 1 June 2017 to 30 September 2018. There may be some spend in certain months which will carry over into the following month. This spend was with Facebook and was to support a number of recruitment campaigns across HMPPS. There was no spend with Twitter or Instagram over this period.</p><p> </p><p>It should be noted that we passed our target to recruit an additional 2,500 prison officers by the end of 2018, seven months early, and have now recruited over 3,500 new staff since that commitment was made in October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Detail of the monthly spend is shown in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Month</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Spend</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jun-17</p></td><td><p>£19,219.20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jul-17</p></td><td><p>£0.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aug-17</p></td><td><p>£0.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sep-17</p></td><td><p>£0.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oct-17</p></td><td><p>£4,600.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nov-17</p></td><td><p>£360.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dec-17</p></td><td><p>£2,254.32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jan-18</p></td><td><p>£3,694.32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feb-18</p></td><td><p>£4,654.32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mar-18</p></td><td><p>£14,854.32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apr-18</p></td><td><p>£71,799.36</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May-18</p></td><td><p>£35,824.32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jun-18</p></td><td><p>£6,094.32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Jul-18</p></td><td><p>£13,834.32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aug-18</p></td><td><p>£5,854.32</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sep-18</p></td><td><p>£7,811.88</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>£171,635.80</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2018-11-06T15:22:05.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997274/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997274/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997274/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-10-29","Ministry of Justice: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much his Department has spent from the public purse on promoted content on (a) Twitter, (b) Facebook and (c) Instagram in each month since June 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","185024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997275","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-11-06","<p>The Department does not routinely pay for promoted content on social media channels and the communications directorate has not directly commissioned any promoted activity on Twitter, Facebook or Instagram since June 2017.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Department has co-funded a National Health Service recruitment campaign with NHS England. Between July and September 2018 the campaign spend across social media was £93,416 and in October 2018 it was £56,147.18.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2018-11-06T16:24:04.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997275/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997275/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997275/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-10-29","Department of Health and Social Care: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how much his Department has spent from the public purse on promoted content on (a) Twitter, (b) Facebook and (c) Instagram in each month since June 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","185025"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997276","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-11-05","<p>The Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government has spent the following amounts on promoted content on Twitter, Facebook and Instagram since June 2017:</p><p>a) Twitter £6,289 (March/April 2018)<br>b) Facebook £41,802 (February/March/April/September 2018)<br>c) Instagram Nil</p><p>All figures include VAT</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-11-05T15:47:31.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997276/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997276/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/997276/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-10-29","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Social Media","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how much his Department has spent from the public purse on promoted content on (a) Twitter, (b) Facebook and (c) Instagram in each month since June 2017.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","185026"
